            <pb n="1r"/>
	<p><lb n="1r1"/>// <g type="symbol" subtype="tennisball"/><!-- Dan: please add this @subtype to our list in EG --> // Oṁ Avighnam<!-- transliteration choice gh still uncertain. See note in apparatus below. Arlo: Now I inclined indeed to take it as gh, not only that this aksara is the most plausibly intended by the scribe, but the form itself is different with ñ in Kawali, here we have unbroken vertical line like latin M--> as·tu, nihan· sakakala ra<lb n="1r2" break="no"/>hyaṁ niskala vas·tu <space type="binding-hole"/> kañcana pun·, turun· ka ra<lb n="1r3" break="no"/>hyaṁ niṁrat·<!-- Aditia: Or should we edit rahyaṁniṁ rat, as we would in an OJ text? Arlo: I favor to stick with separated niṅrat, for the reason that Sundanese usually only have rahyaṅ or rahyaṅta as an honorific appellation, also all historians usually only use the names after for convenience. --> kañcana, ma<space type="binding-hole"/>kaṅuni ka susuhunan· Ayə<lb n="1r4" break="no"/>na ḍi pakuAn· pajajaran· pun·,</p> <p>mulaḥ mo mihape
             <pb n="1v"/><lb n="1v1"/>ḍayəhan· ḍi jayagiri, ḍəṁ ḍayəhan· ḍi <choice><orig>suḍa</orig><reg>suṇḍa</reg></choice><!-- case: suplied nasal ṇ -->-səmbava,</p>
             <p><lb n="1v2"/>Aya ma nu ṅabayuAn· <space type="binding-hole"/> Iña Ulaḥ ḍek· ṅahəryanan· <lb n="1v3"/>Iña, ku na ḍasa, cala<space type="binding-hole"/>gara, kapas· timbaṁ, pare ⌈<lb n="1v4" break="no"/>ḍoṁḍaṁ pun·,</p> <p>maṅ<supplied reason="omitted">k</supplied>a <choice><orig>ḍituḍi</orig><reg>ḍituḍiṁ</reg></choice><!-- case: supplied nasal ṅ/ṁ--> ka para muhara, mulaḥ dek· men·<pb n="2r"/><lb n="2r1" break="no"/>taAn· Iña beya pun·, kena Iña nu puraḥ ḍibuhaya, <lb n="2r2"/>mibuhayakən· na kacari<space type="binding-hole"/>taAn· pun·, nu pagəḥ ṅavaka<lb n="2r3" break="no"/>n· na ḍevasasan·na <space type="binding-hole"/> pun· <g type="symbol" subtype="tennisball"/>, <g type="symbol" subtype="tennisball"/></p>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                   <app loc="1r1">
                       <lem>Avighnam</lem>
                         <rdg source="bib:Pleyte1911_01 bib:Boechari1985-1986_01">Avignam</rdg>
                       <note>The grapheme here represented as <foreign>gh</foreign> is different both from <foreign>k</foreign> and from <foreign>g</foreign> in this group of inscriptions; it resembles the sign that expresses <foreign>ñ</foreign> in the Kawali inscriptions, but is different again from <foreign>ñ</foreign> in the present group of inscriptions. It is also different from the shape of <foreign>gh</foreign> in the Buda/Gunung script (e.g., <bibl><ptr target="bib:Acri2017_01"/><citedRange>637-638</citedRange></bibl>).</note>
                   </app>    
                    <app loc="1v1">
                        <lem source="bib:Pleyte1911_01">ḍəṁ</lem>
                                <rdg source="bib:Boechari1985-1986_01">don</rdg>
                        <note>Boechari's note <quote>Maksudnya: jöŋ</quote> makes clear that his reading is a printing error for <foreign>döŋ</foreign>. Hasan Djafar notes in brackets: <quote>baca: jöṅ</quote>.</note><!-- Dan: here we have two direct quotes from sources that use a different transliteration system; let's make clear in EG that we don't expect adaptation to our system in the case of direct quotes, as distinct from readings used to build <lem> and <rgd>. -->
                    </app>
